	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Fisheries subsidies disciplines in the WTO: challenges and opportunities</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) organised a panel discussion on December 15th 2005, in parallel with the sixth WTO Ministerial Conference, entitled ‘Fisheries subsidies in WTO: challenges and opportunities’.</p><p> The New Zealand trade negotiations minister informed the discussion that: ‘global fisheries subsidies, estimated at a minimum of US$15 billion a year or about 20 per cent of seafood industry revenues, caused large trade distortions... No one can argue subsidies on this scale have no impact on trade. Fishers from developing countries face unfair competition from heavily subsidised competitors from rich industrialised nations. Yet the current subsidies rules just aren’t curbing this problem’.</p><p> The US representative pointed out that: ‘subsidies intended to help expand distant-water fishing fleets that, according to experts and environmental groups, pose the greatest risk to the global fish resources’. He also said that including negotiations on fishing in the Doha round was groundbreaking: ‘For the first time, the WTO is addressing a problem that has direct and immediate consequences, not only for trade but also ... for the marine environment and sustainable development’. He however cautioned that the WTO must stay within its mandate and concentrate on subsidies, leaving issues related to fisheries management to other organisations such as the FAO.</p><p> In their joint press conference, UNEP and WWF pointed to a growing consensus that some subsidies do contribute to fish stock depletion. In their view, amongst the most damaging are those for infrastructure, capital costs, access to foreign countries’ stocks, and price support.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Press statement, UNEP-WWF high-level press event, December 14th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.unep.org/Documents.Multilingual/Default.asp?DocumentI" target="_self">said&quot; target=&quot;&quot;&gt;http://www.unep.org/Documents.Multilin...</a> <br /> UNEP-WWF panel discussion ‘Fisheries subsidies disciplines in the WTO: challenges and opportunities’, December 15th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://assets.panda.org/downloads/15_dec_unep_wwf_final_1.doc" target="_self">http://assets.panda.org/downloads/15_dec_unep_wwf_final_1.doc</a> <br /> Press article, <i>Scoop Independent News</i>, December 15th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0512/S00217.htm" target="_self">http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0512/S00217.htm</a> <br /> US Department of State, international information programmes, December 14th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://usinfo.state.gov/xarchives/display.html?p=washfile-english&amp;y=2005&amp;m=December&amp;x=20051214134428SAikceinawz0.9237329&amp;t=livefeeds/wf-latest.html" target="_self">http://usinfo.state.gov/xarchives/display.html?p=washfile-english&amp;y=...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The position adopted by UNEP and WWF would seem to mirror that of the so-called ‘Friends of Fish’ grouping of countries at the WTO. This advocates that subsidies in the fishing sector require strong rules on disciplines given their potential to contribute to stock depletion through encouraging production distortions and overcapacity. This tends to ignore the flip-side of the coin, which is that subsidies can play an important positive role in improving working conditions, livelihood security and socio-economic well-being in fishing communities.</p><p> This has created a dangerous bias in the subsidies debate at the WTO, which needs to be corrected by developing countries, including ACP countries. Up to now, the debate has also ignored Article 27.1 of the Agreement on Subsidies and Countervailing Measures (ASCM), which recognises that ‘subsidies may play an important role in economic development’.</p><p> Inadequate emphasis on the ‘positive people-oriented effects’ of subsidies could lead to depriving millions of people dependent on fisheries from obtaining legitimate state support to achieve sustainable livelihoods.</p>
		</div>
		
